decision_conditions:
Condition : 7 - No development shall commence until a Construction and Environmental Management Plan (CEMP) for the relevant part of the development has been submitted to and been approved in writing by the local planning authority. The CEMP shall include measures to mitigate the construction effects as part of a coordinated and collaborative approach with surrounding developments, and shall include the following details (although not limited to): 
a)whilst works should take place outside of the nesting season (February - September inclusive), if works are unavoidable during this period, then a site walk over at least 48 hours prior to works commencing is required by a named CIEEM accredited ecologist with experience of working in London to check for any nesting birds in the buildings and vegetation. In the event that a nest is found, an appropriate exclusion zone should be implemented around it until the young have fully fledged (Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended)). The law protects all wild bird species, their eggs and nests;
b)details of measures to be taken to ensure that retained and adjacent habitats, including the wider estate and the adjacent Wimbledon Common and Putney Heath SINC, will not be used for storage or impacted negatively by the works (including, but not limited to vehicle movement, lighting, dust, litter, noise etc.);
c)whilst lighting should be avoided, if lighting is necessary, details of a construction lighting plan outlining how lighting will be prevented from negatively impacting any protected and priority species during construction, in particular commuting bats, or adjacent habitats. This construction lighting plan should follow the best practice industry guidance outlined in the Bat Conservation Trust (BCT) and Institute of Lighting Professionals (ILP) Guidance Note (2023);
d)details of measures to prevent mammal, amphibian or reptile entrapment or harm on site, including in excavations and construction and waste materials left on site;

Condition : 10 - Notwithstanding the details shown on the approved plans and set out in the supporting information, Landscape and Ecological Enhancement and Management Plans shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of any above ground works for each part of the development. The Plan shall include details of all measures to provide biodiversity gain onsite and offsite, including but not limited to: 
- details of native and wildlife friendly planting, including mixed native species hedging, low flowering amenity grass and night scented species. The species list should indicate which species are native and what the wildlife value is; 
- details of all biodiverse roofs (including any Biosolar roofs) including details of extensive substrate base, features to be included within the substrate e.g. rope coils, sand, gravel, etc., and details of any seeding/plug plant choice (in accordance with The Gro Green Roof Code 2021); 
- orientation, target species and location for at least 4x integrated swift bricks/boxes and at least 4x bat boxes to be integrated with the new buildings; 
- details of deadwood habitat;
- a bat sensitive post-construction lighting plan, including lux spill diagrams, to ensure that any lighting will be of a specification that minimises its impacts on bats, onsite habitats and the adjacent Wimbledon Common and Putney Heath SINC in accordance with the BCT and ILP 2023 Guidance Note (including having a colour temperature of <2700k and no uplighters). 
- details on the management to be implemented post-construction shall also be submitted, which shall include management responsibilities and maintenance schedules for all hard and soft landscaped areas as well as the above-mentioned measures to provide biodiversity gain. 
The approved details shall be implemented prior to first occupation of the development and maintained thereafter.
